So, I tried for a while to get the types to actually work out with what I suggested above, and I couldn't figure it out.  So, here's a better proposal with types that actually work:

```python
class Transform(Registrable, Generic[Input, Output]):
    def transform(self, dataset: Iterable[Input]) -> Iterable[Output]:
        raise NotImplementedError

    def __call__(self, dataset: Union[Iterable[Input], Iterable[Iterable[Input]]) -> Union[...]:
        # This is where we'll hide our type checks to handle the union of possible inputs
        raise NotImplementedError

    # no transform_batches; they types don't really work out to do this right, and it's not needed

class InstanceTransform(Transform[Instance, Instance]):
    # transform() is still abstract, but has type Iterable[Instance] -> Iterable[Instance]

    def __call__(self, Union[...]) -> Union[...]:
        # handle case for instance -> instance transforms here

class InstanceToBatchTransform(Transform[Instance, Iterable[Instance]]):
    # transform() is still abstract, but has type Iterable[Instance] -> Iterable[Iterable[Instance]]

    def __call__(self, ...):
        # handle case for instance -> batch transforms here

class BatchToBatchTransform(Transform[Instance, Iterable[Instance]]):
    # transform() is still abstract, but has type Iterable[Iterable[Instance]] -> Iterable[Iterable[Instance]]

    def __call__(self, ...):
        # handle case for batch -> batch transforms, including throwing an error if not already batched

class FileToInstancesTransform(Transform[str, Instance]):
    # transform() is abstract, but is basically a dataset reader, or calls one

    def __call__(self, dataset: Iterable[str]) -> Iterable[Instance]:
        yield from self.transform(dataset)
```

